🚨 REAL ANSWER FOR INTERVIEW

The correct answer is NOT the output.

The correct answer is:

This program has undefined behaviour because it tries to modify a string literal using *x = x[n].
String literals are stored in read-only memory, so the program may crash with segmentation fault.

To print "Alice" safely, you have a few correct options depending on what you want.

✅ ✔ Option 1 — Just print the literal (simplest)

If you only want to print it:

#include<stdio.h>

int main()
{
    char *x = "Alice";
    printf("%s\n", x);
}

✔ Safe
✔ No modification
✔ Works always

✅ ✔ Option 2 — If you want to modify the string later

Then you must store it in writable array memory:

#include<stdio.h>

int main()
{
    char x[] = "Alice";   // array in RAM
    printf("%s\n", x);
}

✔ Now modification is allowed:

x[0] = 'M';   // becomes "Mlice"
✅ ✔ Option 3 — Fix your original program but keep logic

If your intention was to loop and print substrings but also print Alice first:

Correct version:
#include<stdio.h>
#include<string.h>

int main()
{
    int i,n;
    char x[]="Alice";   // changed to array

    n = strlen(x);

    for(i=0; i<=n; i++)
    {
        printf("%s\n",x);
        x[i] = x[i];   // no modification
    }
}
🎯 Most Correct Interview Answer

If interviewer asks:

👉 How to safely print "Alice"?

You say:

If I only need to print it, I can use char *x = "Alice";.
But if I need to modify it, I must use char x[] = "Alice"; so the string is stored in writable memory.

That answer shows you understand memory sections.
